\begin{abstract}
Neural networks excel at many tasks but often struggle with compositional generalization---the ability to blend familiar components into novel configurations. We propose a novel training approach that incorporates an explicit compositional regularization term into the loss function, thereby encouraging the network to form compositional representations. Our method penalizes deviations from predefined compositional patterns in internal representations. We evaluate our approach on synthetic arithmetic datasets, as well as on real-world tasks like machine translation and semantic parsing, comparing models with and without the regularization term. Our experimental results, including dropout tuning and layer configuration studies, indicate improved systematicity scores and reduced test loss under optimal conditions. This work provides insights into enforcing compositionality and bridging the gap between neural networks and human-like reasoning.
