\section{Introduction}
Neural network models have achieved unprecedented performance in a variety of tasks \cite{goodfellow2016deep}. However, they often show limited ability to generalize compositionally, failing to recombine known components in novel ways. Such systematic generalization is a hallmark of human cognition and is critical for robust real-world performance. Recent studies \cite{ito2022compositional} have examined abstract representations to address this shortcoming, though few approaches directly regularize networks to enforce compositional structure. In this work, we propose to augment the learning objective with a compositional regularization term that explicitly penalizes deviations from expected internal compositional patterns. We hypothesize that such an inductive bias will result in improved systematicity and generalization on out-of-distribution combinations. Our contributions include (i) a novel regularization scheme that can be easily integrated into existing architectures, (ii) an extensive evaluation on both synthetic and real-world tasks, and (iii) detailed analyses of internal representations and hyperparameter effects.

\section{Related Work}
Prior work has extensively explored the limitations of neural networks in compositional generalization. Models of abstract representation \cite{ito2022compositional} and meta-learning approaches have been proposed to overcome these issues. In contrast to specialized architectures or meta-learning strategies, our approach introduces a direct regularization term into the training objective. This contrasts with more indirect methods where compositionality is an emergent property rather than an explicit modeling goal. The benefits of directly penalizing deviations from compositional structures align with findings in regularization theory \cite{goodfellow2016deep}; however, our method uniquely targets the internal representations, aiming to bridge the gap between neural and symbolic forms of generalization.

\section{Background}
While neural networks are universal function approximators, their tendency to overfit to statistical biases in training data can impede systematic generalization. Recent work has shown that imposing additional constraints during training can help guide internal representations to respect desired properties. Our approach builds on these findings and integrates a penalty based on pairwise similarities between internal activations corresponding to shared components in input expressions.

\section{Method}
Our proposed method introduces a supplementary regularization term to the standard loss function. Concretely, for a sequence-to-sequence architecture, we compute the standard cross-entropy loss on the output tokens and add a compositional regularization loss computed on hidden states. Given a mini-batch of input sequences, we identify common sub-components (e.g., shared digits or operations in arithmetic expressions) and penalize the squared differences of the corresponding hidden state representations. Mathematically, the regularized loss is
\[
\mathcal{L} = \mathcal{L}_{\text{CE}} + \lambda \, \mathcal{L}_{\text{comp}},
\]
where $\lambda$ is a hyperparameter controlling the strength of the regularization, and 
\[
\mathcal{L}_{\text{comp}} = \sum_{i<j} \mathbb{I}\{s_i \cap s_j \neq \emptyset\}\cdot \operatorname{MSE}(h_i, h_j).
\]
This simple yet effective formulation encourages the model to learn representations in which similar sub-components are embedded near one another, thus promoting compositionality.

